  "transcript": [
    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 0.0,
      "end": 11.68,
      "text": "This is a Libra Vox Recording. All Libra Vox recordings are in the public domain. For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibraVox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 12.28,
      "end": 15.22,
      "text": "Recorded by Vicki Barber, St. John's, Newfoundland.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 16.56,
      "end": 19.62,
      "text": "ASOP's Fables, the Owl, and the Birds.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 20.4,
      "end": 32.04,
      "text": "The Owl is a very wise bird. And once, long ago, when the first oak sprouted in the forest, she called all the other birds together and said to them,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 32.4,
      "end": 45.96,
      "text": "You see this tiny tree? If you take my advice, you will destroy it now when it is small. For when it grows big, the mistletoe will appear upon it, from which bird lime will be prepared for your destruction.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 46.94,
      "end": 59.34,
      "text": "Again, when the first flax was sewn, she said to them, Go and eat up that seed, for it is the seed of the flax, out of which men will one day make nets to catch you.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 59.76,
      "end": 70.96,
      "text": "Once more, when she saw the first archer, she warned the birds that he was their deadly enemy, who would wing his arrows with their own feathers and shoot them.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 70.96,
      "end": 78.56,
      "text": "But they took no notice of what she said. In fact, they thought she was rather mad and laughed at her.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 79.28,
      "end": 86.8,
      "text": "When, however, everything turned out as she had foretold, they changed their minds and conceived a great respect for her wisdom.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 87.66,
      "end": 95.22,
      "text": "Hence, whenever she appears, the birds attend upon her, in the hope of hearing something that may be for their good.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-010",
      "start": 95.22,
      "end": 106.66,
      "text": "She, however, gives them advice no longer, but sits moping and pondering on the folly of her kind. The end of the owl and the birds.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
